                equivalent to <m>\mynot P \to C</m>.
              </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  <m>P \vee C</m>
                </p>
              </answer>
            </task>
            <task>
              <p>
                Since we have proven that <m>\mynot P \to C</m> is true,
                then the disjunction in <xref ref="exer_contradictionproof"/> must also be true.
                Use this to explain why the statement <m>P</m> must be true.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task>
              <p>
                Now explain why <m>P</m> must be true if we prove that the negation of <m>P</m> 
                implies a contradiction.
              </p>
            </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer_sec32-truefalse">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Are the following statements true or false?
            Justify each conclusion.
          </p>
        </introduction>
            <task>
              <statement>
              <p>
                For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                if <m>a</m> is even and <m>b</m> is odd,
                then <m>4</m> does not divide <m>\left( a^2 + b^2 \right)</m>.
              </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  This statement is true.
                  Use a proof by contradiction.
                  So assume that there exist integers  <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that <m>a</m> 
                  is even,
                  <m>b</m> is odd,
                  and 4 divides <m>a^2 + b^2</m>.
                  So there exist integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> such that
                  <me>
                    a = 2m \qquad \text{ and }  \qquad a^2 + b^2 = 4n
                  </me>.
                  Substitute <m>a = 2m</m> into the second equation and use algebra to rewrite 
                  in the form <m>b^2 = 4(n - m^2)</m>.
                  This means that <m>b^2</m> is even and hence, that <m>b</m> is even.
                  This is a contradiction to the assumption that <m>b</m> is odd.
                </p>
              </answer>
            </task>
            <task>
              <statement>
              <p>
                For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                if <m>a</m> is even and <m>b</m> is odd,
                then <m>6</m> does not divide <m>\left( a^2 + b^2 \right)</m>.
              </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  This statement is true.
                  Use a proof by contradiction.
                  So assume that there exist integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that 
                  <m>a</m> is even,
                  <m>b</m> is odd,
                  and 6 divides <m>a^2 + b^2</m>.
                  So there exist integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> such that
                  <me>
                    a = 2m \qquad \text{ and }  \qquad a^2 + b^2 = 6n
                  </me>.
                  Substitute <m>a = 2m</m> into the second equation and use algebra to 
                  rewrite in the form <m>b^2 = 2(3n - 2m^2)</m>.
                  This means that <m>b^2</m> is even and hence, that <m>b</m> is even.
                  This is a contradiction.
                </p>
              </answer>
            </task>
            <task>
              <p>
                For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                if <m>a</m> is even and <m>b</m> is odd,
                then <m>4</m> does not divide <m>\left( a^2 + 2b^2 \right)</m>.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task>
              <statement>
              <p>
                For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                if <m>a</m> is odd and <m>b</m> is odd,
                then <m>4</m> divides <m>\left( a^2 + 3b^2 \right)</m>.
              </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  This statement is true.
                  Use a direct proof.
                  Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be integers and assume they are odd.
                  So there exist integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> such that
                  <me>
                    a = 2m + 1 \qquad \text{ and }  \qquad b = 2n + 1
                  </me>.
                  We then see that
                  <md>
                    <mrow>a^2 + 3b^2 \amp = 4m^2 + 4m + 1 + 12n^2 + 12n + 3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 4\left( m^2 + m + 3n^2 + 3n + 1 \right)</mrow>
                  </md>.
                  This shows that 4 divides <m>a^2 + 3b^2</m>.
                </p>
              </answer>
            </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer_sec33-2">
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Consider the following statement:
        
          <blockquote>
            For each positive real number <m>r</m>, if <m>r^2 = 18</m>, then <m>r</m> is irrational.
          </blockquote>
          </p>
        </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
            <p>
              If you were setting up a proof by contradiction for this statement,
              what would you assume?
              Carefully write down all conditions that you would assume.
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                We would assume that there exists a positive real number <m>r</m> such that 
                <m>r^2 = 18</m> and <m>r</m> is a rational number.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
            <p>
              Complete a proof by contradiction for this statement.
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                Do not attempt to mimic the proof that the square root of 2 is irrational
                (<xref ref="T_squareroot2"></xref>). You should still use the definition of a 
                rational number but then use the fact that 
                <m>\sqrt {18}  = \sqrt {9 \cdot 2}  = \sqrt 9 \sqrt 2  = 3\sqrt 2</m>. 
                So, if we assume that <m>r = \sqrt{18} = 3 \sqrt{2}</m> is rational, then 
                <m>\dfrac{r}{3} = \dfrac{\sqrt{18}}{3}</m> is rational since the rational 
                numbers are closed under division.  Hence, <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is rational and this 
                is a contradiction to <xref ref="T_squareroot2"></xref>.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>

      </exercise>

      <exercise>
