            <task>
              <statement>
              <p>
                For each positive real number <m>x</m>,
                if <m>x</m> is irrational, then <m>\sqrt x</m> is irrational.
              </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  This statement is true since the contrapositive is true.
                  The contrapositive is:
                    <blockquote>
                      For any real number <m>x</m>, if <m>\sqrt{x}</m> is rational, then 
                      <m>x</m> is rational.
                    </blockquote>
                  If there exist integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> with <m>b \ne 0</m> such that 
                  <m>\sqrt{x} = \dfrac{a}{b}</m>,
                  then <m>x^2 = \dfrac{a^2}{b^2}</m> and hence, <m>x^2</m> is rational.
                </p>
              </answer>
            </task>
            <task>
              <p>
                For every pair of real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
                if <m>x + y</m> is irrational,
                then <m>x</m> is irrational and <m>y</m> is irrational.
              </p>
            </task>
            <task>
              <p>
                For every pair of real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
